IS  - 0092-8674 (Print)
IS  - 0092-8674 (Linking)
VI  - 186
IP  - 20
DP  - 2023 Sep 28
TI  - Early Alzheimer's disease pathology in human cortex involves transient cell 
      states.
PG  - 4438-4453.e23
LID - S0092-8674(23)00859-0 [pii]
LID - 10.1016/j.cell.2023.08.005 [doi]
AB  - Cellular perturbations underlying Alzheimer's disease (AD) are primarily studied 
      in human postmortem samples and model organisms. Here, we generated a 
      single-nucleus atlas from a rare cohort of cortical biopsies from living 
      individuals with varying degrees of AD pathology. We next performed a systematic 
      cross-disease and cross-species integrative analysis to identify a set of cell 
      states that are specific to early AD pathology. These changes-which we refer to 
      as the early cortical amyloid response-were prominent in neurons, wherein we 
      identified a transitional hyperactive state preceding the loss of excitatory 
      neurons, which we confirmed by acute slice physiology on independent biopsy 
      specimens. Microglia overexpressing neuroinflammatory-related processes also 
      expanded as AD pathology increased. Finally, both oligodendrocytes and pyramidal 
      neurons upregulated genes associated with β-amyloid production and processing 
      during this early hyperactive phase. Our integrative analysis provides an 
      organizing framework for targeting circuit dysfunction, neuroinflammation, and 
      amyloid production early in AD pathogenesis.
